name: ethoxymethylenemalononitrile
Reason: To predict the melting point of ethoxymethylenemalononitrile, we'll examine the effects of its functional groups compared to a base molecule: - The base unit we can consider is acetonitrile, which has a melting point of -45.7 degrees Celsius (due to its relatively simple structure and presence of a cyano group which provides some dipole-dipole interactions). - An ethoxy group (OC2H5) tends to increase the melting point due to the increase in molecular weight and the potential for hydrogen bonding, which can be approximated as +20 degrees Celsius. - Each additional cyano group (C#N) can be considered to contribute a further +10 degrees Celsius due to increased polarity and dipole-dipole interactions. Ethoxymethylenemalononitrile has one extra cyano group compared to the base molecule. - The presence of the vinyl group (C=C-) can contribute a smaller +5 degrees Celsius due to additional pi-pi interactions and a slight increase in rigidity of the molecular structure. Combining these adjustments, we predict the melting point of ethoxymethylenemalononitrile to be approximately -45.7 (base) + 20 (OC2H5) + 10 (extra C#N) + 5 (vinyl group) = -10.7 degrees Celsius. Since the actual value (65 degrees Celsius) is much higher, upon reevaluating, we should consider that the cyano groups and the potential for intermolecular hydrogen bonding with the ethoxy group have a significantly greater impact on the melting point. It seems that the presence of multiple strong dipole-dipole interactions and possible hydrogen bonding contribute collectively to a much higher increase in melting points than initially predicted.
